<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-281-930  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 281 930.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  May 11 1989 n1163 p20(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Safe and sound? (software safety)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hunter, Philip.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Software publishers are often forced to meet standards ofreliability that are unreasonably high and impossible to verifywith today's technology.andP;  Government and industry should realizethat unrealistic standards that cannot be proven only serve toundermine public confidence in both software suppliers and thosewho purchase the software.andP;  Software publishers can do much moreto improve the reliability of their products, however.andP;  TheBritish Computer Society (BCS) recently put forth a proposalurging government and industry to work together to developimproved safety standards.andP;  Most software publishers agree thatreliability standards and appropriate testing methodologies shouldbe established, despite the difficulties inherent in such anendeavor.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Software ValidationSafetyQuality ControlCriteriaSoftware PublishersPerformance MeasurementLiabilityGovernment RegulationReliability.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>